From: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
Date: Tue, 10 Feb 2026 21:45:16 -0800
Subject: [PATCH] ==== monitor all system rams ====

mm/damon/modules: monitor all system rams by default

DAMON modules set the biggest system ram resource of the system as the
default monitoring target physical address range.  It sounds odd.  The
intention of the design was to reduce the monitoring overhead.  After
all, monitoring non-System RAM area is meaningless for the DAMON
modules.  And users can set the monitoring target address range using
the module prameters.

However, because of the sampling based access check and the adaptive
regions adjustment mechanisms, monitoring non-System RAM areas is no
real overhead.  Meanwhile, on systems having multiple System RAM areas
of big size separated by small non-System RAM areas, this can result in
monitoring only unexpectedly small fraction of the entire system memory.
That is especially common on NUMA systems.  As a result, the default
monitoring target region is just useless.  To my understanding, the
initial user of DAMON was also manually setting the monitoring target
address range for the reason.

Set the phyiscal address range that can cover all System RAM areas of
the system as the default monitoring regions for all (non-sample) DAMON
modules.

Note that the old behavior is documented for DAMON_RECLAIM and
DAMON_LRU_SORT.  So technically speaking, this is changing the
documented behavior.  However, it makes no sense to believe there is a
real use case that really depend on the old weird behavior.  Just change
the behavior and update the document.

In case of DAMON_STAT, it is documented to cover entire physical memory.
So, for the case, the implementation is just wrong.  Same to
DAMON_RECLAIM and DAMON_LRU_SORT, it is unreasonable to believe there
are real users that depend on the wrong implementation.  So commit this
change as a fix.

Signed-off-by: SeongJae Park <sj@kernel.org>
